[{"id":"VR914719","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of an incident green light moving downward through air and perpendicular to a surface of thin film on glass. The glass has n equals 1.50 indicated. Film 1 has n equals 1.40 indicated. Film 2 has n equals 1.60 indicated.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR914719.g01.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two different thin films, Film <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and Film <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, coat the surfaces of two glass blocks. Green, monochromatic light from the same light source is incident on each film-glass combination, as shown in the figure. Films <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> have refractive indexes of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.40\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1.40\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.40</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.60\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1.60\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.60</mn></math></span></span>, respectively, and the glass has a refractive index of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.50\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1.50\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.50</mn></math></span></span>. Each film has the minimum nonzero thickness required for maximum destructive interference between the light reflected from the air-film and film-glass interfaces. Which of the 